  "prompt": "How does international law intersect with national laws on money laundering?",
  "response": "International law and national laws on money laundering intersect in several key ways:\n\n1. International Conventions and Treaties\n- UN Convention against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- Basel Committee guidelines\n- Establish common standards and principles\n\n2. Mutual Legal Assistance\n- Countries collaborate to investigate and prosecute money laundering\n- Sharing of financial intelligence\n- Cross-border legal cooperation\n- Extradition agreements\n\n3. Regulatory Harmonization\n- Standardizing anti-money laundering (AML) procedures\n- Common reporting requirements\n- Similar legal definitions of money laundering\n- Consistent enforcement mechanisms\n\n4. Financial Institution Compliance\n- Banks required to implement international AML standards\n- Know Your Customer (KYC) regulations\n- Suspicious transaction reporting\n- International information sharing protocols\n\n5. Enforcement Mechanisms\n- Sanctions for non-compliance\n- International blacklists\n- Financial penalties\n- Diplomatic pressure\n\n6. Technology and Information Exchange\n- Global financial intelligence networks\n- Real-time transaction monitoring\n- Digital platforms for cross-border cooperation\n\nThese intersections create a comprehensive framework for combating money laundering globally.",
